  "text": "Several lines of evidence suggested that WNKs would be critical regulators of renal ion transport systems: (1) WNK1 and WNK4 are predominantly expressed in the aldosterone-sensitive distal nephron; (2) in addition to hypertension, PHAII patients exhibit hyperkalemia, metabolic acidosis and hypercalciuria consistent with impairment of the normal renal excretion of these ions; (3) PHAII is the mirror image of Gitelman disease that is due to inactivating mutations of the NCC; (4) the PHAII clinical picture is easily reverted by very low doses of thiazide-type diuretics [CITATION_1] .",
